		<item>
		<title>5 Trailblazing Female UX Designers </title>
		<link>https://brainstation.io/blog/5-trailblazing-female-ux-designers</link>
				<pubDate>Fri, 06 Mar 2020 18:20:56 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[BrainStation]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Technology]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[User Experience]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[UX]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Women in Tech]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Female designers]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[ux design]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://blog.brainstation.io/?p=10699</guid>
				<description><![CDATA[<p>To help inspire the next generation of tech innovators, we're featuring five women who are leading the way in UX design for International Women's Day. </p>
<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://brainstation.io/blog/5-trailblazing-female-ux-designers">5 Trailblazing Female UX Designers </a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://brainstation.io/blog">BrainStation® Blog</a>.</p>
]]></description>
								<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Although women now make up half the workforce in the United States, it&#8217;s a well-known fact that the tech industry is dominated by men. According to Adeva, women hold about 25 percent of tech roles and that number drops even lower when looking at the number of women working in leadership roles.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">To help inspire the next generation of tech leaders and innovators, we&#8217;re featuring five women who are leading the way in the UX design industry for International Women&#8217;s Day.&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">From women who are breaking into the industry to UX leaders at some of the world&#8217;s most recognizable companies, here are some of the women who are championing diversity and acting as mentors in their field.&nbsp;</span></p>
<h2><b>Elizabeth Churchill&nbsp;</b></h2>
<p><div id="attachment_10703" style="width: 310px" class="wp-caption alignright"><img aria-describedby="caption-attachment-10703" class="wp-image-10703 size-medium" src="https://d1jxdyr49kipv5.cloudfront.net/prod/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/elizabeth-e1583507932657-300x300.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="300" srcset="https://d1jxdyr49kipv5.cloudfront.net/prod/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/elizabeth-e1583507932657-300x300.jpg 300w, https://d1jxdyr49kipv5.cloudfront.net/prod/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/elizabeth-e1583507932657-150x150.jpg 150w, https://d1jxdyr49kipv5.cloudfront.net/prod/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/elizabeth-e1583507932657-109x109.jpg 109w, https://d1jxdyr49kipv5.cloudfront.net/prod/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/elizabeth-e1583507932657-100x100.jpg 100w, https://d1jxdyr49kipv5.cloudfront.net/prod/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/elizabeth-e1583507932657.jpg 427w" sizes="(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px" /><p id="caption-attachment-10703" class="wp-caption-text">Source: EPIC</p></div></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">There&#8217;s no denying Churchill</span> <span style="font-weight: 400;">is a female leader in UX design. With more than 20 years of experience, this Google exec has seen the industry come a long way and she&#8217;s not afraid to call out the idea that emotions are a female-only trait as &#8220;of course, nonsense.&#8221;&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">&#8220;Acknowledging emotional intelligence and emotionality as being fundamentally human means both men and women benefit in the long run,&#8221; said Churchill in an interview with </span><a href="https://uxdesign.cc/a-series-of-interviews-with-senior-ux-leaders-to-celebrate-international-womens-day-10dc6e354f26"><span style="font-weight: 400;">UX Collective</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">In addition to her role as the Director of UX for Google&#8217;s Material Design (where she has five female and five male reports on her team), Churchill has also worked at tech giants including Yahoo!, Fuji Xerox, and eBay. Plus, she&#8217;s had a long academic career, written books about the design field, and is the current Secretary/Treasurer of the Association for Computing Machinery, the world&#8217;s largest scientific and educational computing society.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>
<h2><b>Lizzie Kelly-Dyson and Georgie Bottomley</b></h2>
<p><div id="attachment_10713" style="width: 898px" class="wp-caption alignright"><a href="https://d1jxdyr49kipv5.cloudfront.net/prod/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/the-duo-copy-e1583509846882.jpg"><img aria-describedby="caption-attachment-10713" class="size-full wp-image-10713" src="https://d1jxdyr49kipv5.cloudfront.net/prod/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/the-duo-copy-e1583509846882.jpg" alt="" width="888" height="300"></a><p id="caption-attachment-10713" class="wp-caption-text">Source: Twelve Scholars and georgiebottomley.com</p></div></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">When Manchester-based Lizzie Kelly-Dyson and Georgie Bottomley wanted to meet more women in the UX design industry, they decided to do something about it.&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">&#8220;We started</span><a href="https://www.ladiesthatux.com/"> <span style="font-weight: 400;">Ladies That UX</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> because we didn&#8217;t know any women in the industry. Around eight people turned up for our first meeting, which was amazing because that&#8217;s eight people that we&#8217;ve never met before,&#8221; said Kelly-Dyson on a podcast called</span><a href="https://hubhopper.com/episode/lizzie-kelly-dyson-step-outside-your-comfort-zone-1579180067"> <span style="font-weight: 400;">Twelve Scholars</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">News of the UX meetup quickly spread and today there are more than 30 Ladies That UX groups in cities across Asia, Europe, Latin America, and North America. There&#8217;s no set format for a meeting, but each Ladies That UX group has a common theme: a community of women in UX who support each other, push the UX boundaries, and promote female skill and talent.&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">&#8220;I hope that every woman has the chance to achieve more through knowing she is not the only one out there, and by finding support in our community,&#8221; said Bottomley about the networking community.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>
<h2><b>Jessica Gaddis</b></h2>
<p><div id="attachment_10705" style="width: 310px" class="wp-caption alignright"><a href="https://d1jxdyr49kipv5.cloudfront.net/prod/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Jessica.jpg"><img aria-describedby="caption-attachment-10705" class="wp-image-10705 size-medium" src="https://d1jxdyr49kipv5.cloudfront.net/prod/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Jessica-e1583509229255-300x300.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="300" srcset="https://d1jxdyr49kipv5.cloudfront.net/prod/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Jessica-e1583509229255-300x300.jpg 300w, https://d1jxdyr49kipv5.cloudfront.net/prod/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Jessica-e1583509229255-150x150.jpg 150w, https://d1jxdyr49kipv5.cloudfront.net/prod/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Jessica-e1583509229255-768x768.jpg 768w, https://d1jxdyr49kipv5.cloudfront.net/prod/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Jessica-e1583509229255-109x109.jpg 109w, https://d1jxdyr49kipv5.cloudfront.net/prod/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Jessica-e1583509229255-100x100.jpg 100w" sizes="(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px" /></a><p id="caption-attachment-10705" class="wp-caption-text">Source: jmgaddis.com</p></div></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Despite growing up with parents who worked in the industry and learning how to code at a young age,</span><a href="http://www.jmgaddis.com/"> <span style="font-weight: 400;">Gaddis</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> didn&#8217;t see herself working in tech. It wasn&#8217;t until she pursued worked on a digital storytelling project in journalism school that she started to consider a career in the tech industry.&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Soon after, Gaddis landed a product design role at Netflix and now works as a Product Designer at Twitter. In an interview for</span><a href="https://xd.adobe.com/ideas/perspectives/interviews/women-ux-meet-jessica-gaddis-former-journalist-turned-self-taught-product-designer-netflix/"> <span style="font-weight: 400;">Adobe&#8217;s XD Idea</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> blog, she spoke about some of the challenges of being a black woman in UX design, including a lack of awareness that UX jobs exist.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">“I’m passionate about giving young women all of the opportunities, all of the knowledge, and all of the information to make more informed decisions about their roles. Even if no one goes into design that’s a black woman ever again, I want women to be able to make those decisions for themselves and know that there is stuff out there for them that maybe they wouldn’t account for, or they wouldn’t even strive to,” said Gaddis.</span></p>
<h2><b>Julie Zhou&nbsp;</b></h2>
<p><div id="attachment_10706" style="width: 310px" class="wp-caption alignleft"><a href="https://d1jxdyr49kipv5.cloudfront.net/prod/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/julie.jpg"><img aria-describedby="caption-attachment-10706" class="wp-image-10706 size-medium" src="https://d1jxdyr49kipv5.cloudfront.net/prod/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/julie-300x300.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="300" srcset="https://d1jxdyr49kipv5.cloudfront.net/prod/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/julie-300x300.jpg 300w, https://d1jxdyr49kipv5.cloudfront.net/prod/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/julie-150x150.jpg 150w, https://d1jxdyr49kipv5.cloudfront.net/prod/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/julie-768x768.jpg 768w, https://d1jxdyr49kipv5.cloudfront.net/prod/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/julie-109x109.jpg 109w, https://d1jxdyr49kipv5.cloudfront.net/prod/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/julie-100x100.jpg 100w, https://d1jxdyr49kipv5.cloudfront.net/prod/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/julie.jpg 800w" sizes="(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px" /></a><p id="caption-attachment-10706" class="wp-caption-text">Source: Diversity in STEAM</p></div></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">If you’ve used Facebook in the past ten years there’s a good chance </span><a href="https://www.juliezhuo.com/"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Julie Zhou</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> played a role in your experience. Zhou is Chinese-American woman who started as an intern at Facebook and, over 14 years, moved her way up to the Vice President of Product Design position. She has since left Facebook and turned her attention to the publishing and public speaking world.&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Despite achieving success at a young age, Zhou was not immune from a common experience many women in the tech industry face: the imposter syndrome.&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">“Experience makes anything look easy, but insecurities never fully disappear. This is true for everyone, especially true for women, and truer still for women in male-dominated fields,” said Zhou on </span><a href="https://medium.com/the-year-of-the-looking-glass/the-imposter-syndrome-9e23e2326d88"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Medium</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Zhou faced those feelings head-on in her much-loved book released last year, </span><a href="https://www.amazon.ca/Making-Manager-What-Everyone-Looks/dp/0735219567"><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">The Making of a Manager: What to Do When Everyone Looks to You</span></i></a><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">.&nbsp;</span></i></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Check it out to find out more about Zhou’s experience of being a leader at a young age and how to unlock your confidence even when you feel like you don’t know what you’re doing.</span></p>
<div class="lead-grid-container">
<div class="lead__card">
<div class="lead__image"><img class="hide--mobile" src="https://d1jxdyr49kipv5.cloudfront.net/prod/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Design3.jpg" alt="Icon"></div>
